Good, quick overview. You might also want to mention a graph-oriented database like Neo4J as yet another model. I think they key driver for choosing a database (aside from just wanting to have something new on your resume), is how much data modeling work you want to do. Relational databases require a lot of up-front work to abstract your data into and E-R model, but reward you with easy ways to carry out complex ad hoc queries. Document stores like MongoDB allow you to store and retrieve data in pretty much the same form that you will use it, so they require less modeling effort and are often good enough for production.

I find this article to be quite intriguing for the fact that it advocates to remove human judgment and also for clearly stating that there is no replacement for data science expertise. Is this article a case of enthusiastic tech marketing? or simply stating the obvious, namely that a better data scientist trumps the better algorithm that trumps the noob data practitioner? Polemics aside, i do agree with the analysis that the next years will see emerging computer aided data science as a well established field for a brand new set of tool vendors. However I have yet to see mature products in this category. The domain specific elements in each concrete use case tend to significantly resize the promises of self-tuning self-data-cleaning tools and services. About data scientists skillz. The analysis is spot on: a good example is for instance time series forecasting. If you are familiar with this domain you probably realize that the gap between a freshman applying arima on a data set and a consumed time serie analyst is incredibly big. So yes, algorithms are better than monkeys. But the real question is another: are d.o.c. algorithms good enough to run unattended?

I tend to agree with you that machine learning right now is VERY hard to master (unless you are a PhD in a related topic). However, with the latest advances in so called autoML (check out DataRobot or some of the related work being done by H2O and other open source communities), you won’t need to know data science in that much detail to figure out the best way to approach a data science problem. I believe in the next 3–4 years it will become quite common to throw a ton of cheap hardware at a problem and have the machine figure out for you what’s the best way to build a model and give you the best quality of predictions. Hence it will become as easy as SQL.
